# RangeError

The **`RangeError`** object indicates an error when a value is not in the set or range of allowed values.

## [Description](#description)

A `RangeError` is thrown when trying to pass a value as an argument to a function that does not allow a range that includes the value.

This can be encountered when:

* passing a value that is not one of the allowed string values to [String.prototype.normalize()](/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global%5FObjects/String/normalize), or
* when attempting to create an array of an illegal length with the [Array](/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global%5FObjects/Array) constructor, or
* when passing bad values to the numeric methods [Number.prototype.toExponential()](/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global%5FObjects/Number/toExponential), [Number.prototype.toFixed()](/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global%5FObjects/Number/toFixed) or [Number.prototype.toPrecision()](/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global%5FObjects/Number/toPrecision).

`RangeError` is a [serializable object](/en-US/docs/Glossary/Serializable%5Fobject), so it can be cloned with [structuredClone()](/en-US/docs/Web/API/structuredClone) or copied between [Workers](/en-US/docs/Web/API/Worker) using [postMessage()](/en-US/docs/Web/API/Worker/postMessage "postMessage()").

`RangeError` is a subclass of [Error](/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global%5FObjects/Error).

## [Constructor](#constructor)

[RangeError()](/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global%5FObjects/RangeError/RangeError)

Creates a new `RangeError` object.

## [Instance properties](#instance%5Fproperties)

_Also inherits instance properties from its parent [Error](/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global%5FObjects/Error)_.

These properties are defined on `RangeError.prototype` and shared by all `RangeError` instances.

[RangeError.prototype.constructor](/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global%5FObjects/Object/constructor)

The constructor function that created the instance object. For `RangeError` instances, the initial value is the [RangeError](/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global%5FObjects/RangeError/RangeError) constructor.

[RangeError.prototype.name](/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global%5FObjects/Error/name)

Represents the name for the type of error. For `RangeError.prototype.name`, the initial value is `"RangeError"`.

## [Instance methods](#instance%5Fmethods)

_Inherits instance methods from its parent [Error](/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global%5FObjects/Error)_.

## [Examples](#examples)

### [Using RangeError (for numeric values)](#using%5Frangeerror%5Ffor%5Fnumeric%5Fvalues)

```
function check(n) {
  if (!(n >= -500 && n <= 500)) {
    throw new RangeError("The argument must be between -500 and 500.");
  }
}

try {
  check(2000);
} catch (error) {
  if (error instanceof RangeError) {
    // Handle the error
  }
}

```

### [Using RangeError (for non-numeric values)](#using%5Frangeerror%5Ffor%5Fnon-numeric%5Fvalues)

```
function check(value) {
  if (!["apple", "banana", "carrot"].includes(value)) {
    throw new RangeError(
      'The argument must be an "apple", "banana", or "carrot".',
    );
  }
}

try {
  check("cabbage");
} catch (error) {
  if (error instanceof RangeError) {
    // Handle the error
  }
}

```

